<div id="review_3862844206" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3862844206" />
    <a title="Teresa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17617298-teresa"><img alt="Teresa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1432153515p2/17617298.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3862844206?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Teresa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Teresa" href="/user/show/17617298-teresa">Teresa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3862844206" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9671665112254194350">“A Taste of Peace (Malibu Series Book 1)” was just that— a taste. The story was not a cliffhanger but a continuation with an abrupt ending. I felt I never got to the meat of the story and will have to read Book 2 to get what I was supposed to get in Book 1—- some kind of meaningful conclusion. The author should have written a better ending even if there is a Book 2. This is why I gave the story three stars.<br/>“A Taste of Peace” is a about Miranda Flowers, an art consultant who has to take a job as </span>
  <span id="freeText9671665112254194350" style="display:none">“A Taste of Peace (Malibu Series Book 1)” was just that— a taste. The story was not a cliffhanger but a continuation with an abrupt ending. I felt I never got to the meat of the story and will have to read Book 2 to get what I was supposed to get in Book 1—- some kind of meaningful conclusion. The author should have written a better ending even if there is a Book 2. This is why I gave the story three stars.<br />“A Taste of Peace” is a about Miranda Flowers, an art consultant who has to take a job as an administrative assistant until she finds a job in her expertise. The admin job is with Peace Holdings, a corporation that is in real trouble since the CEO, Clark Peace is a crook and is in the hospital with cancer. His son, Lachlan, a musician and surfer must step in as CEO to save his inheritance; with the help of his father’s protege and even more corrupt CFO, Britney Ganes. <br />I liked the art angle and learned some interesting things. The romance bugged me because it happened too quickly and I felt the company was in too much trouble financially and criminally for anybody to be thinking about getting laid; let alone falling in love. However, I would still read Book 2 to see how it all ends. Go figure!!<br />I received a free copy of this book and voluntarily reviewed it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9671665112254194350" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


